Description: Translate virtual-monitor local pointer coords to global.
 .
 KWin interprets the coordinates carried by
 ``org_kde_kwin_fake_input::pointer_motion_absolute`` as *global*
 compositor coordinates. The relevant handler in KWin's
 ``src/input.cpp`` connects the protocol request straight to
 ``PointerInputRedirection::processMotion(const QPointF &pos,
 uint32_t time)``, which takes a global position and does no further
 translation based on which output a client might have thought it
 was targeting. See for example the upstream pattern:
 .
     connect(device, &FakeInputDevice::pointerMotionAbsoluteRequested,
             this, [this](const QPointF &pos) {
         m_pointer->processMotion(pos, 0);
         ...
     });
 .
 KRdp's ``PlasmaScreencastV1Session::sendEvent`` computes the pointer
 position in the pipewire stream's *local* pixel space:
 .
     auto logicalPosition = QPointF{
         (position.x() / size().width())  * logicalSize().width(),
         (position.y() / size().height()) * logicalSize().height()};
 .
 When KRdp is running as a dedicated RDP server on a machine that
 also has a physical output (the normal desktop usage and the only
 mode supported by the ``--virtual-monitor client`` flag), the new
 virtual output is placed by KWin at some non-zero origin in the
 compositor's global coordinate space -- typically right of every
 existing output. On a workstation with a 1920x1080 physical
 display, for example, KWin places a 1024x768 virtual output at
 ``(1920, 0)`` or further right depending on how many other virtual
 outputs are already active. Sending the untranslated local
 coordinate ``(512, 384)`` therefore moves KWin's cursor to
 ``(512, 384)`` on the physical output rather than to the centre of
 the virtual output. Every click, keypress, and hot-corner trigger
 then lands on whichever surface is under that global position --
 usually a window on the host's own desktop, or the upper-left
 Overview ("Present Windows") hot corner, which is why users see
 Overview firing repeatedly as they move the mouse inside mstsc.
 .
 The mstsc-rendered cursor still follows the user's mouse because
 Microsoft Remote Desktop draws its own local cursor from the
 cursor-position data sent over the RDP pointer-update channel, so
 the victim's screen looks *almost* correct: the cursor is where
 you expect, the streamed frame shows the right windows, but clicks
 and keystrokes silently miss. The symptom is very confusing.
 .
 This patch resolves the origin of the virtual output by walking
 ``QGuiApplication::screens()`` and picking the QScreen whose size
 matches the virtual monitor's resolution. The virtual monitor's
 name gets mangled on the wl_output side by KWin (it's prefixed
 with ``Virtual-`` and sometimes suffixed), so size is the most
 reliable match when a session is running one virtual monitor at a
 time. The origin is added to ``logicalPosition`` before the
 ``pointer_motion_absolute`` request is sent.
 .
 Lookup is done lazily on each event rather than cached in
 ``start()`` because of a timing hazard: the
 ``ScreencastingStream::created`` callback runs as soon as KWin
 acks the zkde_screencast stream, but KWin may emit the wl_output
 globals describing the new output slightly later, so Qt's screen
 list is not necessarily populated at the exact moment we would
 cache the origin. Iterating over a handful of screens on each
 mouse-move event is cheap and keeps the code obviously correct
 regardless of binding order.
 .
 Button, axis, and key events do not carry coordinates in the
 ``fake_input`` protocol (KWin uses the current cursor position for
 button dispatch), so no translation is needed for those code paths.
